 the course so far.
 In most of the course we have then used a susceptibility 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\chi}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\varepsilon-1\\
 & \mu-1
\end{array}\right),$
\end_inset

 and that is what I have done in the solutions.
 If you assume a completely general 
\begin_inset Formula $6\times6$
\end_inset

 susceptibility, including bianistropic materials, the answers are similar
 but it is more convenient to write them in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\vec{E}\\
\vec{H}
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

 as in the course notes, rather than just 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

.
 Either approach is acceptable.
 It is also acceptable to set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=1$
\end_inset

 as we do for most of the course.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A current 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{J}$
\end_inset

 modifies Ampere's law: 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times\vec{H}=\vec{J}-i\omega\varepsilon_{0}\varepsilon\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 (where we have cancelled the 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-i\omega t}$
\end_inset

 time-dependence in every term).
 Therefore, when we take Faraday's law 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^{-1}\nabla\times\vec{E}=i\omega\mu_{0}\vec{H}$
\end_inset

 and operate 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times$
\end_inset

 on both sides, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\nabla\times\mu^{-1}\nabla\times-\frac{\omega^{2}}{c^{2}}\varepsilon)\vec{E}=i\omega\mu_{0}\vec{J}.
\]

\end_inset

This is indeed of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\vec{E}=\vec{b}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}=\nabla\times\mu^{-1}\nabla\times-\omega^{2}\varepsilon/c^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a linear operator and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}=i\omega\mu_{0}\vec{J}$
\end_inset

 is a given right-hand side.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 solves 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\vec{E}=\vec{b}$
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 is a partner of some representation 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 of the space group.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}^{(\alpha)}\vec{b}=\vec{b}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}^{(\alpha)}=\frac{d_{\alpha}}{|G|}\sum_{g}\chi^{(\alpha)}(g)^{*}\hat{g}$
\end_inset

 is the projection operator for that representation.
 Moreover, by definition of the space group we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 commuting with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 in the space group (this also follows explicitly if 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}\varepsilon=\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}\mu=\mu$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times{}$
\end_inset

 is invariant under rotations and translations), and the definition of the
 space group also requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 leave the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 and the boundary conditions unchanged.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 is linear, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}^{(\alpha)}$
\end_inset

 is merely a linear combination of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}$
\end_inset

's, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 also commutes with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}^{(\alpha)}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\vec{E}=\vec{b}=\hat{P}^{(\alpha)}\vec{b}=\hat{P}^{(\alpha)}\hat{A}\vec{E}=\hat{A}\hat{P}^{(\alpha)}\vec{E}$
\end_inset

, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}(1-\hat{P}^{(\alpha)})\vec{E}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, either 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 is a partner of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}^{(\alpha)}\vec{E}=\vec{E}$
\end_inset

), or the component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 that isn't a partner of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 lies in the null space of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

—that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 is singular and we didn't have a unique solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 in the first place.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

